🔹 What is Dependency in C#?
Dependency means one class relies on another to perform its work.

Example: A Car class depends on an Engine class to run.

Problem: Tight coupling makes code harder to test, maintain, and extend.

Solution: Dependency Injection (DI) — instead of creating dependencies inside a class, we "inject" them from outside.

🔹 Types of Dependency Injection
Constructor Injection

Dependencies are passed via the constructor.

csharp
public class Car
{
    private readonly IEngine _engine;
    public Car(IEngine engine)
    {
        _engine = engine;
    }
    public void Start() => _engine.Run();
}
Setter (Property) Injection

Dependencies are set through properties.

csharp
public class Car
{
    public IEngine Engine { get; set; }
    public void Start() => Engine.Run();
}
Method Injection

Dependencies are passed directly into methods.

csharp
public class Car
{
    public void Start(IEngine engine) => engine.Run();
}
🔹 Syntax with Built-in DI (ASP.NET Core Example)
csharp
// Register services in Program.cs or Startup.cs
services.AddTransient<IEngine, PetrolEngine>();
services.AddScoped<ICar, Car>();

// Resolve via constructor injection
public class Driver
{
    private readonly ICar _car;
    public Driver(ICar car)
    {
        _car = car;
    }
    public void Drive() => _car.Start();
}
🔹 Quick Interview Q&A
Q1: What is dependency injection?  
A: It’s a design pattern where dependencies are provided from outside rather than being created inside a class, reducing coupling and improving testability.

Q2: Difference between tight coupling and loose coupling?  
A: Tight coupling means classes are directly dependent on concrete implementations. Loose coupling means they depend on abstractions (interfaces), making code flexible.

Q3: Which DI type is most common in C#?  
A: Constructor Injection — because it ensures dependencies are available at object creation and supports immutability.

Q4: What’s the role of IoC container?  
A: Inversion of Control (IoC) container automatically manages object creation and dependency resolution, e.g., services.AddScoped<> in ASP.NET Core.

Q5: Why is DI important for unit testing?  
A: It allows injecting mock dependencies, so you can test classes in isolation without relying on real implementations.
